<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Justin Bieber debuted his new song Holy simultaneously with the music video, Thursday night. </p>

<p>In the video, the 26-year-old stars, as a struggling oil miner who is laid-off and evicted, while his on-screen love interest Ryan Destiny, a nurse, finds out her beloved patient died. </p>

<p>The new song reunites the Sorry singer with his I'm the One collaborator Chance the Rapper, who also appears in the video. </p>

<p>Debut: In his Holy music video, released Thursday night, Justin Bieber stars as a struggling oil miner who is laid-off while his on-screen love interest Ryan Destiny, a nurse, finds out her beloved patient died</p>

<p>Struggling: The down-on-their-luck couple then find out they have been evicted and recieve a kind gesture from a stranger</p>

<p>Directed by Justin's Never Let You Go, U Smile, Next to You and No Brainer collaborator Colin Tilley, the moving video comes in at five and a half minutes long. </p>

<p>The video opens with Justin and Ryan waking up together in bed, sharing sweet moments over coffee before he heads off to work in an oil field and she goes to work to care for an elderly patient. </p>

<p>'That the way you hold me, hold me, hold me, hold me, hold me,' Justin sings in the chorus of the song as montages of the couple together flash on screen. 'Feels so holy, holy, holy, holy, holy.'</p>

<p>Justin then gets to work in a grey long sleeve T-shirt, brown overalls and a yellow safety hat, covered in oil residue. </p>

<p>Start of day: The video opens with Justin and Ryan waking up together in bed </p>

<p>Stolen moments: They share sweet moments in the morning sun before heading their separate ways for the day</p>

<p>Holy: 'That the way you hold me, hold me, hold me, hold me, hold me,' Justin sings in the chorus of the song as montages of the couple together flash on screen. 'Feels so holy, holy, holy, holy, holy </p>

<p>Hard work: Justin then gets to work in a grey long sleeve T-shirt, brown overalls and a yellow safety hat, covered in oil residue </p>

<p>The second-half of the chorus seems relevant to Justin's off-screen romance with wife Hailey Bieber, who he initially after just months of dating in 2018. </p>

<p>'On God / Runnin' to the altar like a track star,' he sings. 'Can't wait another second.' </p>

<p>Justin sings while at work and Ryan is shown to be having a joy-filled day bringing flowers to her patient, and dancing with others. </p>

<p>Then things take a turn for the worse, as the music stops, Justin and his co-workers gather around to be informed the plant is shutting down due to a 'global situation.' </p>

<p>As the song resume, the lyrics continue to seem to be personal to the Never Say Never hitmaker 'They say we're too young and / The pimps and the players say, "Don't go crushin" / Wise men say fools rush in / But I don't know.' </p>

<p>Care: Ryan, a nurse,g oes to work to care for an elderly patient</p>

<p>Happy start: Justin sings while at work and Ryan is shown to be having a joy-filled day</p>

<p>Dance break: She even danced with patients and co-workers</p>

<p>Personal: The second-half of the chorus seems relevant to Justin's off-screen romance with wife Hailey Bieber, who he initially after just months of dating in 2018. 'On God / Runnin' to the altar like a track star,' he sings. 'Can't wait another second' </p>

<p>Ryan is seen sitting on the empty bed where he patient was earlier in the day. </p>

<p>Chance the Rapper then comes in for his verse, which takes place at night in a greenhouse with Justin behind him. </p>

<p>Justin walks home from his workday, as the sunsets, alone on a dirt road, after his truck broke down. </p>

<p>He gets home just in time to find their landlord posting an eviction notice as Ryan screams and cries while he holds her. </p>

